WEBVTT

00:00:25.880 --> 00:00:28.710
Thank you,
and I want to welcome you to the

00:00:28.800 --> 00:00:34.180
Enterprise IT track of Apple's 2003
Worldwide Developer Conference.

00:00:34.280 --> 00:00:38.180
Today, what we'd like to do
is review what Apple,

00:00:38.290 --> 00:00:42.140
our customers, and you, our developers,
have been doing with Apple and the

00:00:42.140 --> 00:00:44.790
Enterprise over the last 12 months.

00:00:44.920 --> 00:00:47.690
We also have a special guest,
Tom Yaeger from InfraWorld,

00:00:47.820 --> 00:00:51.530
who is going to give us his perspective
on Apple and the Enterprise.

00:00:51.810 --> 00:00:55.760
And finally,
we're going to get a sneak preview

00:00:55.940 --> 00:00:58.950
of Apple OS X Panther for servers.

00:00:59.120 --> 00:01:01.700
So, let's get right into it.

00:01:02.140 --> 00:01:04.300
A little background first.

00:01:04.420 --> 00:01:10.300
IT technology decisions are made
today in a very difficult environment,

00:01:10.300 --> 00:01:13.420
and any of you involved in IT, I'm sure,
realize this.

00:01:13.420 --> 00:01:17.860
The IT managers are being
asked to do more with less.

00:01:17.860 --> 00:01:20.630
Licensing costs seem to keep rising.

00:01:20.630 --> 00:01:23.580
Maintenance costs seem to keep rising.

00:01:23.580 --> 00:01:27.410
The only thing that doesn't seem to rise
very much is the economy these days.

00:01:27.460 --> 00:01:33.120
And in this challenging environment,
one of the key decisions being faced by

00:01:33.120 --> 00:01:36.650
IT managers is the following dilemma.

00:01:36.900 --> 00:01:39.830
Everyone would like to
have the flexibility,

00:01:39.920 --> 00:01:42.540
the low cost,
the freedom to choose vendors,

00:01:42.560 --> 00:01:47.240
the freedom to choose the right tool
for the job that you get by basing

00:01:47.520 --> 00:01:50.440
your environment on open standards,
multi-vendor,

00:01:50.440 --> 00:01:51.600
and heterogeneous solutions.

00:01:51.600 --> 00:01:56.640
However, this comes with a cost,
because some assembly is required.

00:01:57.840 --> 00:02:00.350
Putting together things in
your own shop takes time,

00:02:00.350 --> 00:02:04.210
takes money, and so it's incredibly
tempting for people to go

00:02:04.210 --> 00:02:07.310
with a single vendor solution,
where that single vendor

00:02:07.310 --> 00:02:11.060
will integrate things,
make it reliable, hopefully,

00:02:11.070 --> 00:02:14.800
and the downside of that is
that you lose flexibility,

00:02:14.950 --> 00:02:18.180
and you lose some potential cost savings,
and these days cost

00:02:18.540 --> 00:02:20.510
savings are pantomount.

00:02:20.960 --> 00:02:26.430
Now, over the last five or so years,
open source-based solutions are

00:02:26.430 --> 00:02:30.580
increasingly seen as an alternative
to the status quo of just writing

00:02:30.580 --> 00:02:32.330
your check to your vendor every year.

00:02:32.340 --> 00:02:37.020
Now, open source, by definition,
drives you to an environment

00:02:37.020 --> 00:02:41.570
with open standards,
multi-vendor, and heterogeneity.

00:02:41.580 --> 00:02:44.870
Open source means that you're
going to spend some of your

00:02:44.870 --> 00:02:48.140
time putting things together,
making sure that they're

00:02:48.140 --> 00:02:50.390
managed properly,
installing them.

00:02:50.950 --> 00:02:55.030
You're dealing, by definition,
with a heterogeneous system.

00:02:55.290 --> 00:02:59.000
The real challenge here is
to get those benefits of open

00:02:59.000 --> 00:03:00.240
source without a huge cost.

00:03:00.280 --> 00:03:03.420
Now the benefits are, I think, huge.

00:03:03.470 --> 00:03:08.650
Over the past 20, 30 years,
software has been developed

00:03:08.770 --> 00:03:12.450
in the same way that,
you know, a few minor changes that

00:03:25.300 --> 00:03:29.990
This change is now noticed
big time by the IT industry.

00:03:30.080 --> 00:03:30.690
Why?

00:03:30.980 --> 00:03:33.370
Well, number one, cost savings.

00:03:33.380 --> 00:03:36.700
Or I should say perceived cost savings,
because the price tag on

00:03:36.700 --> 00:03:38.190
open source seems great.

00:03:38.350 --> 00:03:40.750
And we'll come back to that issue.

00:03:41.010 --> 00:03:43.950
Number two, by its very nature,
by the development

00:03:44.050 --> 00:03:48.040
process of open source,
open source tends to be interoperable.

00:03:48.040 --> 00:03:51.090
They tend to hew very
closely to open standards.

00:04:28.520 --> 00:04:31.250
Apple has responded to
various cert alerts.

00:04:31.400 --> 00:04:35.590
We tend to respond extremely quickly
to those things because of the open

00:04:35.610 --> 00:04:38.480
source underpinnings of Mac OS X.

00:04:41.170 --> 00:04:43.370
Another big benefit is code reuse.

00:04:43.600 --> 00:04:47.440
And code reuse goes without
saying in the open source world.

00:04:47.630 --> 00:04:49.940
And as you all know,
the best code and the most

00:04:49.940 --> 00:04:52.840
efficient code is the code
that you didn't have to write.

00:04:52.970 --> 00:04:55.530
And in the open source world,
the ability to go and grab

00:04:55.530 --> 00:04:59.000
something from one project and
reuse it in another project is key.

00:04:59.000 --> 00:05:02.990
And then finally, a deep talent pool.

00:05:03.310 --> 00:05:06.430
You are leveraging with open
source a talent pool of over a

00:05:06.430 --> 00:05:10.220
million programmers worldwide
contributing to various projects.

00:05:10.240 --> 00:05:12.630
And in fact,
there's increasing numbers of

00:05:12.630 --> 00:05:17.220
people that you can hire in your own
IT shops who know and love open source

00:05:17.220 --> 00:05:20.920
and can manage that Apache server
pretty much in their sleep.

00:05:20.940 --> 00:05:25.470
So it's really a myth that you
can't find people to manage these

00:05:25.470 --> 00:05:27.940
Unix or open source programs.

00:05:28.170 --> 00:05:33.160
Now, over the last five years,
the same five years that we've

00:05:33.160 --> 00:05:37.500
been developing Mac OS X,
open source has virtually exploded.

00:05:37.540 --> 00:05:40.860
And up on the screen are
just a few of the literally

00:05:40.860 --> 00:05:43.140
thousands of projects out there.

00:05:43.310 --> 00:05:48.420
If you go to SourceForge and you
do a search on open source projects

00:05:48.420 --> 00:05:51.850
on SourceForge for Mac OS X,
today there are over

00:05:51.850 --> 00:05:55.280
1,300 projects there,
ranging from huge projects

00:05:55.280 --> 00:05:58.060
to small projects,
but really it's a testament to

00:05:58.060 --> 00:06:02.970
the activity in this environment.

00:06:03.950 --> 00:06:07.020
The price tag looks
right for open source,

00:06:07.070 --> 00:06:10.100
but it can sometimes
come with a hidden cost.

00:06:10.100 --> 00:06:14.560
And the hidden cost is that
there is some assembly required.

00:06:14.560 --> 00:06:19.660
And that means that it's not always
delivered with the management tools,

00:06:19.940 --> 00:06:23.550
with the vendor backing,
with the integration out of the

00:06:23.650 --> 00:06:26.860
box that you would like to have,
and so that creates more work for you.

00:06:26.860 --> 00:06:29.700
In a perfect world,
what you would have is you would

00:06:29.750 --> 00:06:33.700
have all of the benefits of open
source that we just talked about,

00:06:34.000 --> 00:06:38.090
plus the reliability and support
that you get from a major vendor,

00:06:38.090 --> 00:06:42.080
plus ease of deployment, installation,
management,

00:06:42.080 --> 00:06:45.520
etc., all of the fit and finish things.

00:06:45.680 --> 00:06:48.780
And if you had all those together,
you would achieve the nirvana of

00:06:48.780 --> 00:06:51.640
lower total cost of ownership.

00:06:52.100 --> 00:08:11.300
[Transcript missing]

00:08:13.420 --> 00:08:15.620
So this is our strategy.

00:08:15.650 --> 00:08:18.300
Leverage open source,
not just in the product,

00:08:18.440 --> 00:08:19.690
but outside the box.

00:08:19.750 --> 00:08:21.600
Let you leverage open source.

00:08:21.610 --> 00:08:24.960
And what we add is the fit and
finish of a commercial product,

00:08:24.970 --> 00:08:29.080
the management tools,
the installation tools, everything,

00:08:29.150 --> 00:08:32.430
so that your total cost
of ownership goes down.

00:08:32.910 --> 00:08:35.800
Now this strategy is
reflected in our products.

00:08:35.800 --> 00:08:39.110
It's reflected in our
software with Mac OS X,

00:08:39.310 --> 00:08:40.770
Jaguar going to Panther.

00:08:40.960 --> 00:08:46.460
It's reflected in our hardware products
from laptops to XServe to XServe RAID.

00:08:46.740 --> 00:08:49.720
And it's reflected in
our service offerings.

00:08:49.970 --> 00:08:52.660
Service offerings we know need to
be different for the enterprise.

00:08:52.720 --> 00:08:55.330
This is an area where we are investing,
and will continue to

00:08:55.350 --> 00:08:57.680
invest in the future.

00:08:57.680 --> 00:09:00.700
So let's start out by
looking at software.

00:09:02.860 --> 00:09:06.870
As was mentioned this morning by Steve,
Mac OS X is Unix-based.

00:09:06.980 --> 00:09:08.730
And it's not just any Unix.

00:09:08.780 --> 00:09:14.640
It is industrial-strength BSD Unix,
together with CMU Mach,

00:09:14.670 --> 00:09:17.470
to provide a highly
responsive environment,

00:09:17.470 --> 00:09:19.910
not just for servers,
but also for clients.

00:09:20.040 --> 00:09:23.640
A key feature,
or a key thing to remember here,

00:09:23.680 --> 00:09:28.270
is that we use exactly the same
source code base when we build

00:09:28.280 --> 00:09:31.340
Mac OS X Server as we do Mac OS X client.

00:09:31.340 --> 00:09:33.280
It's the same kernel.

00:09:33.330 --> 00:09:35.480
This is important because it
makes sure we don't have to

00:09:35.490 --> 00:09:37.490
split our engineering resources.

00:09:37.710 --> 00:09:41.020
And as we fix bugs or security
issues in one product,

00:09:41.160 --> 00:09:43.120
they get automatically
fixed in the other product.

00:09:43.120 --> 00:09:44.620
And the two leverage each other.

00:09:44.840 --> 00:09:48.990
And it allows us to move very
quickly to add new features to

00:09:48.990 --> 00:09:51.090
the Unix base of our system.

00:09:51.500 --> 00:09:55.000
Now, on top of this,
Apple has done something that

00:09:55.320 --> 00:09:58.210
nobody else has been able to do,
even though many people

00:09:58.290 --> 00:10:01.280
have tried over the years,
which is on top of a

00:10:01.280 --> 00:10:06.880
Unix-based underpinning to
add state-of-the-art graphics,

00:10:06.990 --> 00:10:11.070
frameworks,
and user interface support on the client.

00:10:11.200 --> 00:10:16.120
So graphics, as you heard this morning,
state-of-the-art support for OpenGL,

00:10:16.120 --> 00:10:21.320
for PDF-based graphics, for 2D graphics,
frameworks from Cocoa to

00:10:21.350 --> 00:10:25.840
Carbon to Java frameworks,
and then user interface,

00:10:25.840 --> 00:10:27.780
our killer Aqua user interface.

00:10:27.840 --> 00:10:33.880
And wait till you get a
chance to try-- I love Expose.

00:10:33.880 --> 00:10:37.040
It's going to be a godsend
on the user interface.

00:10:37.040 --> 00:10:42.620
Now, on top of these frameworks,
Apple integrates in the

00:10:42.620 --> 00:10:44.640
box useful applications.

00:10:44.640 --> 00:10:47.910
And we all know and love-- there's
a ton of applications in there,

00:10:48.020 --> 00:10:49.380
including the iLife applications.

00:10:49.560 --> 00:10:53.700
But what I want to focus on are
the end user applications that

00:10:53.700 --> 00:10:55.500
are important to the enterprise.

00:10:55.500 --> 00:10:58.000
In fact,
they're critical to the enterprise.

00:10:58.000 --> 00:11:00.790
They're end user applications
that mission critical in

00:11:00.900 --> 00:11:02.790
any enterprise I know of.

00:11:03.330 --> 00:11:05.150
First of all, mail.

00:11:05.230 --> 00:11:10.060
So Apple has a great mail client,
just got a whole lot better in Panther.

00:11:10.060 --> 00:11:16.350
Integrates IMAP support, POP support,
can interact with any mail server

00:11:16.470 --> 00:11:18.300
based on those two standards out there.

00:11:18.300 --> 00:11:20.960
Starting with Panther, can support SSL.

00:11:20.960 --> 00:11:24.750
So we're taking the mail app forward,
and we'll continue to support that

00:11:24.840 --> 00:11:27.320
mission-critical app in the Enterprise.

00:11:28.040 --> 00:11:31.390
Address Book integrates with LDAP,
and more and more corporations

00:11:31.390 --> 00:11:35.980
are moving to base their addresses
and employee information on LDAP.

00:11:35.980 --> 00:11:40.090
Address Book accesses all
that information seamlessly.

00:11:40.310 --> 00:11:42.930
Safari, I just,
I want to spend a little bit more

00:11:43.040 --> 00:11:45.900
time on Safari because you don't
often think about it this way,

00:11:45.900 --> 00:11:49.090
but the web browser is actually
a mission-critical application

00:11:49.180 --> 00:11:50.320
for the enterprise these days.

00:11:50.320 --> 00:11:52.970
As applications get
deployed to the desktop,

00:11:53.070 --> 00:11:56.320
whether it be Oracle or
PeopleSoft or other applications,

00:11:56.320 --> 00:12:00.380
the browser is actually often the
front end of those applications.

00:12:00.860 --> 00:12:04.110
Now, to me, the exciting thing is this.

00:12:04.110 --> 00:12:07.450
In the past,
when we worked with enterprise

00:12:07.450 --> 00:12:11.750
software developers like
Oracle or like PeopleSoft,

00:12:11.750 --> 00:12:16.550
they would come to us and say, well,
this doesn't work quite right on

00:12:16.550 --> 00:12:18.840
Internet Explorer or on Netscape.

00:12:18.840 --> 00:12:20.890
And we would sort of
look at them and say,

00:12:20.890 --> 00:12:23.740
well, yeah,
we wish that would work better, too.

00:12:23.740 --> 00:12:26.860
It's a totally different
ballgame now with Safari.

00:12:26.860 --> 00:12:30.820
Safari's based on
open-source project HTML.

00:12:30.860 --> 00:12:32.550
We take that in-house.

00:12:32.690 --> 00:12:35.240
We add all the
Safari underpinnings around that.

00:12:35.250 --> 00:12:38.360
That is totally under our
control now to make it the best

00:12:38.360 --> 00:12:40.370
and fastest browser on the Mac.

00:12:40.400 --> 00:12:44.170
And the conversations now that
we have with enterprise software

00:12:44.280 --> 00:12:48.430
developers like PeopleSoft and
Oracle are totally different because

00:12:48.430 --> 00:12:52.360
when they come to us and say,
we'd like to make sure that PeopleSoft

00:12:52.410 --> 00:12:56.500
works really great with Safari,
we say, great, no problem.

00:12:56.500 --> 00:12:59.350
We're going to fix Safari to
work the best it can possibly

00:12:59.350 --> 00:13:00.720
work with PeopleSoft.

00:13:00.860 --> 00:13:04.600
And you have PeopleSoft now announcing
they're going to qualify on Safari.

00:13:04.680 --> 00:13:09.110
So the world for enterprise
browsers on the Mac just got a

00:13:09.110 --> 00:13:11.710
whole lot better with Safari.

00:13:12.250 --> 00:13:15.070
Java, of course,
Apple is recognized for having

00:13:15.100 --> 00:13:18.980
the best client implementation of
Java Standard Edition out there,

00:13:18.980 --> 00:13:21.340
not just by us,
but by others in the industry,

00:13:21.340 --> 00:13:23.360
including Sun Microsystems.

00:13:23.520 --> 00:13:27.150
Java is the application
language of choice for many

00:13:27.150 --> 00:13:30.680
places in the enterprise today,
not just on the client,

00:13:30.680 --> 00:13:32.450
but on the server as well.

00:13:32.620 --> 00:13:37.090
And last but not least,
that key mission-critical

00:13:37.200 --> 00:13:41.450
client-side application,
which is Microsoft Office.

00:13:41.560 --> 00:13:45.460
And the Mac business
unit continues to work,

00:13:45.510 --> 00:13:48.390
continues to invest in Microsoft Office.

00:13:48.470 --> 00:13:51.410
That will, you know,
it's very interesting because we are

00:13:51.410 --> 00:13:55.950
the only Unix-based system out there
that also runs Microsoft Office.

00:13:56.090 --> 00:13:59.900
One of the things that this has done
for us is that anybody who needs

00:13:59.900 --> 00:14:03.250
to run Unix for whatever reason,
in the past,

00:14:03.360 --> 00:14:06.810
they would typically have a PC sitting
right next to it because they

00:14:06.820 --> 00:14:08.650
also had to run Microsoft Office.

00:14:08.810 --> 00:14:10.900
With the Mac,
those two systems collapsed.

00:14:10.900 --> 00:14:16.670
And that's a major place where we're
making inroads in the enterprise.

00:14:17.430 --> 00:14:24.650
So let's shift gears for a
bit to Mac OS X Server Jaguar.

00:14:25.430 --> 00:14:31.780
Mac OS X Server packages just a
ton of services that can run on any

00:14:31.780 --> 00:14:37.070
server installation in the Enterprise,
and has those key services that

00:14:37.070 --> 00:14:38.090
are important to the Enterprise.

00:14:38.100 --> 00:14:39.340
I'll just go through a few of those.

00:14:39.360 --> 00:14:42.210
In the area of security, we run Kerberos.

00:14:42.410 --> 00:14:46.110
I'm going to go into a lot
more detail later on Kerberos,

00:14:46.210 --> 00:14:49.050
but Kerberos is key to single sign-on.

00:14:49.060 --> 00:14:51.650
Just leave that there for now.

00:14:51.650 --> 00:14:53.090
Come back to it.

00:14:53.600 --> 00:14:57.070
Directory, of course,
almost any enterprise today

00:14:57.070 --> 00:15:01.330
has a LDAP directory server,
either LDAP or Active Directory,

00:15:01.410 --> 00:15:03.340
which is really kind of a flavor of LDAP.

00:15:03.380 --> 00:15:07.090
Web services, we have Apache,
which is the leading web

00:15:07.110 --> 00:15:10.470
server on the planet,
supporting HTTP and all the

00:15:10.470 --> 00:15:14.770
modules that you would want to
support things like SOAP and XML,

00:15:14.770 --> 00:15:16.790
RPC, and things like that.

00:15:16.840 --> 00:15:20.190
Mail,
a very nice mail server supporting IMAP,

00:15:20.190 --> 00:15:21.720
POP, and web mail.

00:15:22.270 --> 00:15:26.620
File service,
every file service known to man from

00:15:26.620 --> 00:15:30.060
AFP to SMB with Samba to NFS to FTP.

00:15:30.060 --> 00:15:32.620
Print service with CUPS print serving.

00:15:32.620 --> 00:15:37.200
Internet printing protocol, LPR,
which Unix people know and love,

00:15:37.200 --> 00:15:38.900
Apple Talk printing.

00:15:38.900 --> 00:15:43.140
And finally, last but not least,
secure shell login,

00:15:43.140 --> 00:15:45.140
remote login with SSH.

00:15:45.140 --> 00:15:49.610
Now, an important issue here
is that Apple doesn't just

00:15:49.650 --> 00:15:51.570
take all of... You know,
these are all the things that we're

00:15:51.570 --> 00:15:51.770
going to talk about in a minute.

00:15:51.830 --> 00:15:53.730
These are mostly open source projects.

00:15:53.740 --> 00:15:56.200
So we have leveraged
them into the product,

00:15:56.200 --> 00:15:59.110
but we don't just take the
projects and toss them onto

00:15:59.210 --> 00:16:00.850
the CD and ship them to you.

00:16:00.860 --> 00:16:04.430
We actually spend a lot
of time integrating them,

00:16:04.430 --> 00:16:09.060
making sure they perform well,
making sure that they're QA'd,

00:16:09.110 --> 00:16:12.530
making sure that our management
tools can manage all these things.

00:16:12.560 --> 00:16:17.020
So that's the major advantage of
getting this from Apple versus just

00:16:17.140 --> 00:16:21.780
trying to assemble your own out on
the web on something like Linux.

00:16:21.780 --> 00:16:23.180
Next.

00:16:25.100 --> 00:16:29.150
Now, to do this,
we provide management tools.

00:16:29.210 --> 00:16:32.270
We provide GUI management tools
for remote management of all the

00:16:32.410 --> 00:16:34.840
services you saw on the last slide.

00:16:35.030 --> 00:16:38.460
In doing so,
we also make sure that we continue

00:16:38.460 --> 00:16:41.170
to support terminal-based or
command line tool management,

00:16:41.170 --> 00:16:43.750
because there are many people
out there that still like

00:16:43.750 --> 00:16:45.170
to manage things that way.

00:16:45.280 --> 00:16:48.920
So we don't disable that branch
of managing all of these services.

00:16:48.940 --> 00:16:52.670
You can take your pick,
choose whatever works best for you.

00:16:53.000 --> 00:16:59.260
We also support SNMP for our
products so that the tools from

00:16:59.260 --> 00:17:04.360
other major management vendors,
such as Tivoli, HP with OpenView, or CA,

00:17:04.360 --> 00:17:10.590
those projects are enabled to manage
the SNMP aspects of our products.

00:17:10.600 --> 00:17:13.400
So we have really complete
management solution,

00:17:13.460 --> 00:17:20.060
and I'll talk a bit after Tom speaks
in some of the very exciting directions

00:17:20.060 --> 00:17:22.080
we're going to be taking there.

