It had a PostScript user interface.

00:32:29.500 --> 00:32:33.320
It had an object-oriented
programming language.

00:32:33.320 --> 00:32:37.670
It had BSD,
which you know how I feel about that,

00:32:37.670 --> 00:32:42.030
running on top of Mach,
which I also thought was very cool.

00:32:43.010 --> 00:32:46.800
And I figured, it's a real shame that
Next didn't make it,

00:32:46.900 --> 00:32:49.660
because I wanted all those
things together in one machine.

00:32:51.910 --> 00:32:58.420
Now, on the System 5 side,
there were interesting goings-on as well.

00:32:58.540 --> 00:33:04.670
AT&T had licensed System 5
to 11 different companies who

00:33:04.670 --> 00:33:08.110
wound up selling it for the PC.

00:33:08.540 --> 00:33:11.460
And it started out cheap,
and it started out rich.

00:33:11.460 --> 00:33:16.810
I think it was,
I think the SEO distribution

00:33:16.810 --> 00:33:20.810
was something like 25 floppies.

00:33:20.990 --> 00:33:23.690
And then it began to deteriorate.

00:33:23.960 --> 00:33:27.530
Each of the 11 vendors started
creating proprietary versions of it.

00:33:27.530 --> 00:33:30.140
And they couldn't get together.

00:33:30.140 --> 00:33:33.790
They didn't really want to get together
and make this thing interoperate.

00:33:33.840 --> 00:33:37.900
So it degenerated to the point
where these vendors started going

00:33:37.930 --> 00:33:40.040
out of business very rapidly.

00:33:40.040 --> 00:33:43.460
The 11 licensees shrunk to four.

00:33:43.460 --> 00:33:48.810
There are now four companies
in the commercial Unix space,

00:33:49.110 --> 00:33:50.240
plus Apple.

00:33:50.240 --> 00:33:56.360
And none of those four companies are
the original 11 licensees of System 5,

00:33:56.380 --> 00:34:04.860
which gives you a perspective of how
quickly and deeply things fell apart.

00:34:05.340 --> 00:34:12.600
The last bit of our little history lesson
is what wiped out microcomputer unix.

00:34:12.700 --> 00:34:18.450
In 1995,
Microsoft introduced Windows NT 4.0.

00:34:18.450 --> 00:34:23.790
And in 1996,
Microsoft introduced some free software

00:34:23.800 --> 00:34:27.150
called the Windows NT 4 Option Pack.

00:34:27.620 --> 00:34:31.110
Microsoft had learned the lesson
with Internet Explorer that the

00:34:31.190 --> 00:34:35.700
best way to get customers is to
give wonderful software away.

00:34:35.700 --> 00:34:42.240
And with the NT4 Option Pack,
Microsoft drove right through Unix by

00:34:42.520 --> 00:34:48.560
giving customers back all the things
that the Unix vendors had taken away.

00:34:48.600 --> 00:34:55.300
So all the enterprise features like
guaranteed messaging and transactions and

00:34:55.300 --> 00:34:59.750
database management and web applications,
they were in NT,

00:34:59.790 --> 00:35:02.690
and you couldn't find them in any Unix.

00:35:02.700 --> 00:35:08.320
It was a bit of a drag,
but I have to give Microsoft credit.

00:35:08.320 --> 00:35:11.000
They really did a fabulous job on NT4.

00:35:13.780 --> 00:35:20.190
Now, consolidation trend was
obviously already underway.

00:35:20.200 --> 00:35:23.380
Unix, the Unix market had consolidated.

00:35:23.650 --> 00:35:29.310
Most of microcomputers were pulled
into Windows operating systems.

00:35:30.000 --> 00:36:25.800
[Transcript missing]

00:36:26.200 --> 00:36:31.780
We also had a trend of commoditization,
and that's an easy one to describe.

00:36:31.780 --> 00:36:38.140
Commoditization is the practice
of a vendor deciding that all they

00:36:38.140 --> 00:36:41.960
have to do is wait for everybody
else to develop technology,

00:36:41.960 --> 00:36:45.200
then find a way to make
it with cheaper plastic,

00:36:45.200 --> 00:36:49.640
and then sell it back to the market
for a dollar less than the other one.

00:36:49.880 --> 00:36:54.490
And this cycle keeps wrapping
around until IT just says,

00:36:54.490 --> 00:36:57.330
"I'm not going to buy this anymore."

00:36:57.970 --> 00:37:04.750
When we got into 2002, 2003, IT said,
we're done.

00:37:04.830 --> 00:37:08.110
I don't see any reason to buy
a Pentium 4 desktop when my

00:37:08.200 --> 00:37:10.500
Pentium 3 is handling my workload.

00:37:10.500 --> 00:37:17.450
Why should I pay $1,000 more for
a dual Xeon rack machine when

00:37:17.620 --> 00:37:21.600
a dual Pentium 3 goes for $999?

00:37:21.600 --> 00:37:24.020
It runs cooler and quieter.

00:37:25.040 --> 00:37:32.230
IT was making decisions based on criteria
that had never been present before,

00:37:32.310 --> 00:37:34.140
and I'll get to those in a minute.

00:37:36.870 --> 00:37:40.980
Apple jumped into the
market in the early 2000s.

00:37:41.310 --> 00:37:44.740
I don't think it was on
the radar for most people.

00:37:44.740 --> 00:37:51.300
They were behind the scenes developing
Rhapsody and the early versions of OS X.

00:37:51.300 --> 00:37:56.400
When the PowerBook first hit,
it was amazing.

00:37:56.400 --> 00:38:02.560
When the gigahertz PowerBook,
15-inch titanium PowerBook, hit,

00:38:02.720 --> 00:38:07.890
it destroyed the market
for high-end PC notebooks.

00:38:08.210 --> 00:38:13.100
What had, up to that date,
been sold as portable workstations,

00:38:13.100 --> 00:38:16.400
and I carried these things
routinely because I write code

00:38:16.400 --> 00:38:21.080
and I do digital media work and
I need that kind of firepower,

00:38:21.390 --> 00:38:27.540
I immediately hung up all of my PCs,
the best of the PC notebooks I had,

00:38:27.600 --> 00:38:30.650
and replaced them all with
one machine that to this day

00:38:30.960 --> 00:38:34.030
I take everywhere with me.

00:38:36.000 --> 00:38:39.160
Apple declared this the
year of the notebook,

00:38:39.170 --> 00:38:44.300
and they carried the technology they had
introduced with the 15-inch PowerBook to

00:38:44.300 --> 00:38:49.870
the 17-inch and to the 12-inch,
and they continued to take more and

00:38:49.870 --> 00:38:52.450
more share away from PC vendors.

00:38:52.460 --> 00:38:57.500
They also set standards
for portable computers that

00:38:57.710 --> 00:39:03.710
PC vendors never managed to match,
which remains true.

00:39:04.490 --> 00:39:09.500
You look at things like battery life,
gigabit Ethernet, wireless networking,

00:39:09.500 --> 00:39:13.490
which Apple pioneered and Apple still
does better than anybody else,

00:39:13.590 --> 00:39:18.900
a gorgeous display with a 3D
accelerator built into it.

00:39:19.950 --> 00:39:23.990
When I picked up a
PowerBook for the first time,

00:39:24.090 --> 00:39:26.610
aside from its looks,

00:39:27.180 --> 00:39:29.580
There are two things that
really grabbed me about it.

00:39:29.680 --> 00:39:30.450
Well, three things.

00:39:30.470 --> 00:39:35.920
The first one was that it ran BSD,
and that just hooked me immediately.

00:39:36.240 --> 00:39:40.560
The second thing is
what Sons James Gosling,

00:39:40.610 --> 00:39:43.200
the father of Java, told me.

00:39:43.220 --> 00:39:44.680
He carries a PowerBook.

00:39:44.740 --> 00:39:48.090
He does all his programming
on a PowerBook now.

00:39:48.240 --> 00:39:53.940
He loved the alien landing beacon
that blinks on and off when

00:39:54.120 --> 00:39:57.380
the machine is in suspend mode.

00:39:58.440 --> 00:40:02.930
And when I asked him
the single best feature,

00:40:03.020 --> 00:40:06.300
tell me the one thing that makes you
carry this machine everywhere you go,

00:40:06.300 --> 00:40:09.200
he said, the lid works.

00:40:11.820 --> 00:40:17.900
That is no small thing for those of us
who have been using Windows for forever.

00:40:18.920 --> 00:40:23.160
Now,
we saw PowerBook redefine its market.

00:40:23.160 --> 00:40:27.350
We've seen XServe redefine
its market with price,

00:40:27.350 --> 00:40:29.040
with ease of management.

00:40:29.040 --> 00:40:34.110
And now we see XServe RAID redefining
the market for networked storage,

00:40:34.110 --> 00:40:39.880
not only by bringing prices down,
but by maintaining enterprise features,

00:40:39.880 --> 00:40:45.710
like redundant power supplies,
redundant controllers, swappable,

00:40:45.890 --> 00:40:47.560
removable trays.

00:40:51.580 --> 00:40:54.890
It's not an easy ride for Apple, though.

00:40:54.990 --> 00:40:57.120
And we learned that,
InfoWorld learned that,

00:40:57.180 --> 00:41:02.100
when we started running editorial
on Apple's enterprise efforts.

00:41:02.240 --> 00:41:06.930
We got a lot of letters from readers,
we got a lot of letters from PC vendors,

00:41:07.010 --> 00:41:10.540
a lot of screaming phone
calls from PC vendors,

00:41:10.540 --> 00:41:12.100
who were telling us,

00:41:12.880 --> 00:41:15.090
I haven't heard this before.

00:41:15.160 --> 00:41:18.170
I'm not sure I buy it,
because I've been watching

00:41:18.170 --> 00:41:21.430
Apple for 20 years,
and what you're telling me

00:41:21.430 --> 00:41:25.710
about Apple doesn't map with
my version of the facts.

00:41:26.280 --> 00:41:31.340
The first thing they said is,
OS X is not mature.

00:41:31.380 --> 00:41:33.330
Look how long Windows has
been on the market.

00:41:33.400 --> 00:41:37.000
Look how long Solaris
has been on the market.

00:41:37.040 --> 00:41:38.160
This is a newcomer.

00:41:38.320 --> 00:41:40.340
I don't trust it.

00:41:40.610 --> 00:41:43.420
Remember what I said
about the next machine?

00:41:43.430 --> 00:41:46.780
That was back in the early 90s.

00:41:46.780 --> 00:41:48.820
And it had these three things in it.

00:41:48.820 --> 00:41:52.130
It had BSD, which dates back to 1978.

00:41:52.240 --> 00:41:56.170
It has Mach, which dates back to 1985.

00:41:56.290 --> 00:42:00.930
And it has the next step APIs and
graphical user interfaces

00:42:00.930 --> 00:42:03.800
that date back to 1988.

00:42:03.800 --> 00:42:08.970
I don't think you can compare
to that combination of

00:42:08.970 --> 00:42:12.300
underpinnings for maturity.

00:42:12.570 --> 00:42:14.860
Hardware is slow.

00:42:14.860 --> 00:42:17.120
This applied to some of
the Macs a long time ago.

00:42:17.230 --> 00:42:19.140
It certainly doesn't
apply to current hardware.

00:42:19.140 --> 00:42:26.480
And the most concise observation
I've ever heard about performance was

00:42:26.910 --> 00:42:30.180
uttered by Sun's Greg Papadopoulos.

00:42:30.180 --> 00:42:35.160
He's their CTO and all-around visionary,
and probably the third

00:42:35.160 --> 00:42:37.350
smartest person I've ever met.

00:42:38.270 --> 00:42:42.090
And he said, "When you're talking about
performance in computers,

00:42:42.290 --> 00:42:44.490
forget megahertz.

00:42:44.550 --> 00:42:47.590
It is all about throughput.

00:42:47.660 --> 00:42:51.790
If you can't get data
from the CPU to memory,

00:42:51.940 --> 00:42:56.730
if you can't get data
from memory to storage,

00:42:56.760 --> 00:42:56.890
it's all over.

00:42:56.940 --> 00:43:00.540
It really doesn't matter how
fast your chip burns cycles.

00:43:00.540 --> 00:43:04.460
It's going to spend most of
its time waiting for I/O."

00:43:05.060 --> 00:43:06.870
Max are more expensive than PCs?

00:43:06.940 --> 00:43:07.390
Sure.

00:43:07.460 --> 00:43:13.760
I mean, most of us remember the
2FX and the Quadra series.

00:43:13.760 --> 00:43:16.880
And they were just scary.

00:43:16.880 --> 00:43:20.860
You had to love the thing because
you were going to take out a

00:43:20.860 --> 00:43:23.170
second mortgage to pay for it.

00:43:24.320 --> 00:43:29.700
But with the current market,
if you compare feature for feature

00:43:29.700 --> 00:43:33.620
what Mac does with Power Books,
what Apple does with

00:43:34.040 --> 00:43:37.330
its Power Mac systems,
which don't get much

00:43:37.330 --> 00:43:40.890
attention at shows like this,
but thank goodness they did the keynote

00:43:40.940 --> 00:43:42.860
the way they did the keynote today.

00:43:42.860 --> 00:43:46.260
Power Macs are cool, powerful machines.

00:43:46.330 --> 00:43:49.930
Where can you find a
Unix workstation anymore?

00:43:50.040 --> 00:43:54.540
We saw the best example of
that technology this morning.

00:43:54.540 --> 00:43:56.690
It's just going to keep getting better.

00:43:56.700 --> 00:44:01.220
And on the XServe, once again,
if you line up features,

00:44:01.230 --> 00:44:06.920
if you line up overall power,
if you line up IO throughput capability,

00:44:06.920 --> 00:44:07.960
forget it.

00:44:07.960 --> 00:44:10.690
PCs can't get there from here.

00:44:11.910 --> 00:44:13.800
There aren't enough apps.

00:44:13.800 --> 00:44:16.840
Yeah, all of us remember
walking through CompUSA,

00:44:16.940 --> 00:44:19.520
and there were 12 aisles
of Windows software,

00:44:19.520 --> 00:44:23.040
and there was one lonely
aisle of Mac software.

00:44:23.040 --> 00:44:25.620
And it was, you know,
games for two-thirds of it,

00:44:25.620 --> 00:44:28.020
and then a little, you know,
a little column of

00:44:28.020 --> 00:44:29.780
productivity applications.

00:44:30.340 --> 00:44:32.800
That's not true anymore.

00:44:32.800 --> 00:44:36.750
I'm not saying that we don't
have some distance to come.

00:44:37.040 --> 00:44:38.390
There is still a gap.

00:44:38.440 --> 00:44:43.140
There is certainly more software
available for Windows PCs.

00:44:43.140 --> 00:44:47.720
There is certainly more open source
software available for Linux.

00:44:47.760 --> 00:44:51.950
But if you look at the richness
of the software available

00:44:52.050 --> 00:44:56.580
for the BSD operating system,
how easy it is to port to OS X,

00:44:56.580 --> 00:45:00.320
and if you look at just
what Apple has done,

00:45:00.320 --> 00:45:00.320
you can see that there is a gap.

00:45:30.590 --> 00:45:33.910
And as far as I'm concerned,

00:45:34.340 --> 00:45:38.700
The pace of new development
is just staggering.

00:45:38.700 --> 00:45:42.310
So when I say there's more to come,
I don't think it's going to

00:45:42.310 --> 00:45:43.500
take long to play that out.

00:45:45.580 --> 00:45:50.740
I have some observations from
watching the market in general

00:45:50.830 --> 00:45:56.180
that relate to the state of the
market that Apple is playing in.

00:45:56.310 --> 00:45:58.620
IT in general.

00:45:58.670 --> 00:46:00.100
It's been hard to figure
out what they want.

00:46:00.100 --> 00:46:04.200
I remember I've got a close
friend in marketing at Microsoft.

00:46:04.370 --> 00:46:08.410
We went out to dinner,
and we had a couple glasses of wine,

00:46:08.410 --> 00:46:13.790
and then we got a bottle of wine,
and then we got another bottle of wine.

00:46:13.940 --> 00:46:17.540
And when we were done and we were
in the cab going back to the hotel,

00:46:17.750 --> 00:46:23.420
he said, "You know that Microsoft would
just love to give customers

00:46:23.770 --> 00:46:28.460
what they want?" And I said,
"That's really great.

00:46:28.630 --> 00:46:30.850
I'm glad that's so."

00:46:34.370 --> 00:46:39.400
And then, in utter frustration,
he looked at me and said,

00:46:39.400 --> 00:46:46.280
"So what the hell do customers want?"
Because you couldn't nail it down.

00:46:46.320 --> 00:46:48.780
It was a list this long,
and it was a different list

00:46:49.170 --> 00:46:52.270
for every vertical market,
and for every line of business,

00:46:52.550 --> 00:46:54.270
and every little segment.

00:46:54.300 --> 00:46:59.850
But now, thanks to the recession,
thanks to IT getting tired

00:46:59.850 --> 00:47:03.970
of having no innovation,
we come down to some very

00:47:04.060 --> 00:47:06.300
simple set of requirements.

00:47:06.300 --> 00:47:09.910
I want rapid payback,
which doesn't mean I can take

00:47:10.300 --> 00:47:16.000
IBM Global Services and give these guys
with suits and briefcases eight years

00:47:16.000 --> 00:47:18.300
to bang on enterprise integration.

00:47:18.300 --> 00:47:22.270
I want solutions that work when
I pull them out of the box.

00:47:22.300 --> 00:47:24.300
And I want payback in six years.

00:47:24.300 --> 00:47:26.300
And I want payback in six months.

00:47:26.300 --> 00:47:28.300
And if you can't give it to me,
I'm not going to talk to you.

00:47:28.300 --> 00:47:32.300
I want minuscule long-term
costs of ownership.

00:47:32.300 --> 00:47:36.300
I don't want to have to maintain a crew
of wizards to keep my stuff running.

00:47:36.580 --> 00:47:37.940
Zero lock-in?

00:47:37.980 --> 00:47:41.180
Don't tell me I can never
leave this platform.

00:47:41.220 --> 00:47:44.630
Don't tell me that this architecture
you built this machine with

00:47:44.630 --> 00:47:46.220
doesn't run anywhere else.

00:47:46.230 --> 00:47:48.140
Not acceptable.

00:47:48.420 --> 00:47:51.510
Purposeful innovation isn't
about bells and whistles.

00:47:51.570 --> 00:47:54.600
There's lots of cute
stuff on Apple machines.

00:47:54.690 --> 00:47:59.320
I have disagreements with
the people at Apple about the

00:47:59.320 --> 00:48:02.050
blinky lights on the XServe.

00:48:02.490 --> 00:48:07.180
Apple has been criticized in the past for
not putting any lights on its machine.

00:48:07.260 --> 00:48:10.980
I remember one of their servers that
had a completely blank front panel

00:48:10.980 --> 00:48:13.400
except for one little light for power.

00:48:13.450 --> 00:48:18.590
And now, of course,
I would say they've overcorrected a bit.

00:48:21.390 --> 00:48:26.650
Now, the best summary of these
requirements came to me from a

00:48:26.650 --> 00:48:29.560
gentleman named Winston Bumpus.

00:48:29.580 --> 00:48:31.600
That's the coolest name.

00:48:31.770 --> 00:48:34.720
And he works at Novell,
and he's probably the fourth

00:48:34.780 --> 00:48:36.110
smartest person I've ever met.

00:48:36.190 --> 00:48:42.460
And he says, the only reason to buy
something is it makes you money,

00:48:42.500 --> 00:48:46.350
it saves you money,
or it's required by the government.

00:48:48.830 --> 00:48:51.210
And I thought, thank God.

00:48:51.240 --> 00:48:55.670
I mean, I can throw away my 30-page
summary of IT requirements

00:48:55.730 --> 00:48:57.030
and just replace it with that.

00:48:57.080 --> 00:49:00.390
I thought it was sweet,
and I really do think

00:49:00.390 --> 00:49:02.360
it describes reality.

00:49:02.810 --> 00:49:08.170
Most of you know how well Apple has
done to adapt to these simpler and

00:49:08.170 --> 00:49:10.860
far more demanding requirements.

00:49:10.860 --> 00:49:16.640
Apple's execution,
its ability to take these requirements

00:49:16.700 --> 00:49:19.180
and turn them into products,
has been fabulous.

00:49:19.700 --> 00:49:23.700
That's because the execution
is based on customer feedback.

00:49:23.700 --> 00:49:26.700
It's based on the anticipation
of customer needs.

00:49:26.700 --> 00:49:31.360
When the PowerBook came out,
didn't you think it was serious

00:49:31.360 --> 00:49:34.480
overkill for a portable machine?

00:49:34.480 --> 00:49:40.340
Who on earth wanted to carry gigabit
Ethernet around with them on a notebook?

00:49:40.340 --> 00:49:45.140
And of course, now we actually use it,
now that we can get a gigabit

00:49:45.180 --> 00:49:47.940
Ethernet switch for 80 bucks.

00:49:50.100 --> 00:49:55.630
And Apple put in the box
very quick deployment.

00:49:55.990 --> 00:49:57.540
We get an out-of-the-box experience.

00:49:57.540 --> 00:49:58.980
The notebooks work immediately.

00:49:58.980 --> 00:50:02.420
XServe walks you through
the initial configuration.

00:50:02.420 --> 00:50:07.260
XServe RAID, when I saw that demo,
I just about fell out of my chair.

00:50:07.260 --> 00:50:10.140
It was so easy to set up,
and it was so easy to use,

00:50:10.150 --> 00:50:11.850
and it was so resilient.

00:50:12.200 --> 00:50:15.140
We were walking around the back
and pulling out power supplies

00:50:15.270 --> 00:50:18.470
while it was still running,
and yanking drives out of the thing,

00:50:18.470 --> 00:50:22.700
and shutting segments down
from the administrative tools,

00:50:22.700 --> 00:50:24.400
and it just kept, yeah, whatever.

00:50:24.400 --> 00:50:26.250
And that's what I want.

00:50:29.570 --> 00:50:37.490
IT wants solutions that are consistent
across the vendor's product line.

00:50:37.730 --> 00:50:40.190
and no compromises.

00:50:40.230 --> 00:50:45.840
I don't want machines that make me make
choices about what I can do because

00:50:45.870 --> 00:50:49.880
the technology isn't capable of it,
or because the vendor has

00:50:49.890 --> 00:50:53.180
decided to impose choices on me.

00:50:55.500 --> 00:51:00.290
I think that as we watch how
these trends are panning out,

00:51:00.390 --> 00:51:06.040
we see a couple of things that
will make sure that Apple stays

00:51:06.540 --> 00:51:09.030
relevant in the enterprise IT market.

00:51:09.660 --> 00:51:13.390
And as we watch and as we see
