Panther Server includes LDAP directory

01:02:41.790 --> 01:02:44.820
and Kerberos authentication.

01:02:44.820 --> 01:02:51.300
It's LDAP v2 or v3,
and we've taken it a step further.

01:02:51.300 --> 01:02:56.240
We put LDAP on top of
Berkeley DB so it scales.

01:02:57.230 --> 01:02:59.710
thousands of records supported.

01:02:59.760 --> 01:03:03.440
But that's not enough scaling for us.

01:03:03.640 --> 01:03:09.920
So we also added the ability to support
local replicas for high availability.

01:03:10.050 --> 01:03:13.270
So if one replica goes down,
you can find the other replica.

01:03:13.300 --> 01:03:14.320
LDAP keeps running.

01:03:14.330 --> 01:03:15.920
Kerberos also keeps running.

01:03:15.920 --> 01:03:19.530
And remote replicas,
so that you can go and

01:03:19.530 --> 01:03:23.640
set up a remote replica,
and a geographic site can serve

01:03:23.750 --> 01:03:26.100
up all the same information.

01:03:26.100 --> 01:03:29.430
So this is actually incredible
state-of-the-art scalability

01:03:29.430 --> 01:03:31.090
for both LDAP and Kerberos.

01:03:31.090 --> 01:03:33.980
And I'll come back to the importance
of those two things in a moment.

01:03:33.980 --> 01:03:35.730
Actually, right now.

01:03:35.740 --> 01:03:41.130
So one of the biggest challenges,
actually, I was talking to a CIO who said

01:03:41.130 --> 01:03:45.830
one of their biggest costs on their
help desk was people calling up

01:03:45.890 --> 01:03:48.830
because they forgot their password.

01:03:48.840 --> 01:03:52.240
And it's easy to find,
the reason for this is that

01:03:52.240 --> 01:03:56.080
almost every network service ends
up requiring its own password.

01:03:56.100 --> 01:03:59.430
And so you have two choices, really.

01:03:59.680 --> 01:04:04.150
Either you can just choose
the same password for every

01:04:04.150 --> 01:04:06.510
service on your network.

01:04:06.520 --> 01:04:09.760
That's incredibly insecure, by the way,
and is frowned upon by

01:04:09.760 --> 01:04:12.330
any security expert,
because if you crack into one service,

01:04:12.380 --> 01:04:13.800
you've cracked all the passwords.

01:04:13.800 --> 01:04:17.350
But people do that because there's
really no other easy choice.

01:04:17.350 --> 01:04:19.490
The other thing you can
do is have a different,

01:04:19.490 --> 01:04:23.180
you can force users to have different
passwords by enforcing a password policy,

01:04:23.250 --> 01:04:25.930
so they have to actually
choose different passwords.

01:04:25.940 --> 01:04:28.740
For every service that they sign on to.

01:04:28.740 --> 01:04:31.970
Of course, then you've left the user
with only one choice,

01:04:31.970 --> 01:04:34.640
which is to write down all
their passwords and put it

01:04:34.740 --> 01:04:37.530
up on their bulletin board,
which you can see as you walk

01:04:37.530 --> 01:04:38.840
around some of these places.

01:04:38.840 --> 01:04:42.050
So what everyone is moving
to is single sign-on.

01:04:42.050 --> 01:04:43.840
What is single sign-on?

01:04:43.840 --> 01:04:47.840
One password provides secure
access to all your services,

01:04:47.840 --> 01:04:51.000
but it's done in a secure
way using Kerberos.

01:04:51.000 --> 01:04:55.780
The way this works,
the Kerberos server authenticates.

01:04:55.780 --> 01:04:59.080
So the Kerberos server
authenticates the user on login.

01:04:59.080 --> 01:05:02.800
They're handed out a token,
actually a ticket-granting token,

01:05:02.800 --> 01:05:06.440
and they can use that key to log
in and authenticate themselves to

01:05:06.440 --> 01:05:08.820
any other service on the network.

01:05:08.870 --> 01:05:13.230
So Apple's strategy here on the
server is to make sure every

01:05:13.330 --> 01:05:18.380
service we deploy is Kerberized,
which is the term people use.

01:05:20.500 --> 01:05:23.430
And likewise,
to make sure the clients that access them

01:05:23.550 --> 01:05:25.880
on the client are Kerberized as well.

01:05:26.050 --> 01:05:31.140
So, Panther gets us, I would say,
you know, 95% of the way there.

01:05:31.140 --> 01:05:33.030
There might be a few
things we've forgotten,

01:05:33.040 --> 01:05:34.370
but we'll quickly fix them.

01:05:34.540 --> 01:05:36.820
In fact, Panther's not shipping yet,
so let us know about

01:05:36.820 --> 01:05:38.460
things that we've left out.

01:05:38.490 --> 01:05:41.840
But that is, I think,
going to be incredibly important for any

01:05:41.890 --> 01:05:45.620
enterprise deployment of any software,
really.

01:05:45.620 --> 01:05:48.780
So, we are well along that path.

