with Apache and with other things.

01:06:57.740 --> 01:07:01.380
So what we are doing with Panther is
we are taking all of those

01:07:01.500 --> 01:07:05.510
pieces and putting them together,
including tools for managing

01:07:05.510 --> 01:07:09.020
JBoss so it can become a
deployment environment as well.

01:07:09.890 --> 01:07:16.470
And we are including with that
a tool for easily migrating.

01:07:16.480 --> 01:07:21.400
There are slight differences in how
J2EE objects are deployed between,

01:07:21.400 --> 01:07:25.510
or EJBs are deployed between
different application servers.

01:07:25.560 --> 01:07:30.370
We have some tools, for example,
to very easily take a BEA EJB and

01:07:30.370 --> 01:07:33.610
import that into JBoss automatically.

01:07:33.640 --> 01:07:36.870
So this is going to be a very slick
set of tools for anybody in the

01:07:37.160 --> 01:07:39.680
enterprise developing J2EE applications.

01:07:39.800 --> 01:07:44.810
I'd like to talk about Mail Server.

01:07:48.200 --> 01:07:51.160
With Panther,
we are moving to the Postfix mail server,

01:07:51.160 --> 01:07:55.320
which many agree is the most
robust and scalable open email

01:07:55.320 --> 01:07:57.040
solution on the market today.

01:07:57.040 --> 01:08:00.920
Now,
we're not just putting Postfix in there.

01:08:01.020 --> 01:08:04.020
Postfix provides SMTP support.

01:08:04.040 --> 01:08:08.610
We're also including Cyrus to
support IMAP and POP.

01:08:08.660 --> 01:08:11.900
And you'll notice we have
Webmail and mailing lists.

01:08:12.050 --> 01:08:15.440
For Webmail, we're using Squirrelmail,
so we're integrating in Squirrelmail.

01:08:15.440 --> 01:08:18.030
For mailing lists,
we're integrating Mailman

01:08:18.040 --> 01:08:19.580
right in Panther Server.

01:08:19.630 --> 01:08:22.820
So you have a complete mail solution.

01:08:27.720 --> 01:08:31.170
